  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Criminal Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering criminal statute)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\n3. State Level:\nMany states have their own money laundering statutes that complement federal laws\n\n4. International Cooperation:\n- The U.S. works with international organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force)\n\nThese statutes generally:\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalize the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money\n- Establish penalties including fines and imprisonment\n- Create reporting and recordkeeping requirements\n\nEnforcement is primarily conducted by agencies like:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\nPenalties can include significant financial sanctions and potential criminal prosecution.",
